Description: Smaller fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The rear shows a convex side with traces of an object like a leather bag or a vessel neck, in the break one deep and wide impressions of a turned cord with a width of about 0.4 cm. Only a small part of the original surface is preserved with an impression of an oval scarab-like seal. The motif shows a squatting Seth-animal, facing towards the left, in front of it very small hieroglyphic signs, a nfr on top of what looks like nb n, behind the head were another signs that are not preserved here. Same motif as EA86791.
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Amara West (Nubia), E14.7 temple magazine
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
